DOCUMENT();       

loadMacros("PG.pl",
           "PGbasicmacros.pl",
           "PGchoicemacros.pl",
           "PGanswermacros.pl",
           "PGgraphmacros.pl",
           "extraAnswerEvaluators.pl",
           "PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
           "PGgraphmacros.pl"
           );
       
TEXT(beginproblem()); # standard preamble to each problem.


$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;


$x0 = -1;
$x1 = random(1,3,1);
$dx = $x1+1;
$num = random(2,4,1);
$power = random(2,4,1);
$h0 = $num**$power;
$h0_sq = $h0**2;
$h1 = 1/$h0;
$h1_disp = "1/$h0";
$b = 1/$h0**(2/$dx);
$b_disp = "(1/$h0_sq)^(1/$dx)";
$top_p = $dx-2;
$almost = $h0**($top_p);
$a = ($almost)**(1/$dx);
$a_disp = "($almost)^(1/$dx)";
$b_rd = round($b*10000)/10000;
$a_rd = round($a*10000)/10000;
$ans = "($a_disp)*($b_disp)^x";

BEGIN_TEXT
Question 36:
$BR $SPACE $BR
Find a formula for the EXPONENTIAL function which satisfies the given conditions:
$BR
$SPACE
$BR
\( \displaystyle f($x1) = \frac{1}{$h0} \) $SPACE $SPACE and $SPACE $SPACE \( f($x0) = $h0 \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
\( f(x) = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}
$BR
(try to avoid any approximations, or be sure to approximate your values for $BITALIC a $EITALIC and $BITALIC b $EITALIC in your formula to at least 4 decimal places to avoid significant rounding error)

END_TEXT

ANS( fun_cmp($ans,vars=>'x'));


SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR 
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR 

Since \( f(x)=ab^x \), \( f($x0)= ab^{$x0} \) and \( f($x1)=ab^{$x1} \).
$BR
Since we know that \( f($x0)=$h0 \) and \( f($x1)=$h1_disp \), we can say that \( ab^{$x0} = $h0 \) and \( ab^{$x1} = \frac{1}{$h0} \).  Forming ratios, we have
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE 
\( \displaystyle \frac{ab^{$x1}}{ab^{$x0}} = \frac{1/$h0}{$h0} = \frac{1}{$h0_sq} \)
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE
\( \displaystyle b^{($x1 - $x0)} = b^{$dx} = \frac{1}{$h0_sq} \)
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE
\( \displaystyle b = \sqrt[$dx]{ \frac{1}{$h0_sq}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt[$dx]{$h0_sq}} \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
Thus, our formula is \( f(x)=a \left( \frac{1}{\sqrt[$dx]{$h0_sq}} \right)^x \).  Use ($x0, $h0) to get
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE
\( \displaystyle a \left( \frac{1}{\sqrt[$dx]{$h0_sq}} \right)^{$x0} = $h0 \)
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE
\( \displaystyle a = ($h0) \cdot \left( \frac{1}{\sqrt[$dx]{$h0_sq}} \right) = \frac{$h0}{\sqrt[$dx]{$h0^2}} = $h0^{(1-2/$dx)} = \sqrt[$dx]{$almost} \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
Therefore \( \displaystyle f(x) = \left( \sqrt[$dx]{$almost} \right) \left( \frac{1}{\sqrt[$dx]{$h0_sq}} \right)^x \).
$BR
END_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();   # This should be the last executable line in the problem.